# Cross-file repo-audit golden set — planted defects in cases/repo-audit/orderdesk/.
# Each defect is INVISIBLE in any single file: recognizing it requires reading
# across the listed `files`. `category` uses run-clean.py's VOCAB. `primary` is
# the set of files a correct finding may be attributed to (strict scoring).
# Run: python3 evals/run-repo-audit.py    (see evals/README.md).
{"id": "p1_idor", "category": "idor", "files": ["orders.py", "orders_service.py"], "primary": ["orders.py", "orders_service.py"], "note": "GET /orders/{id} delegates to OrderService.get_order, which fetches by primary key with NO ownership/tenant filter. The route has `user` but never scopes to it; the service looks like a generic data-access helper. Neither file alone shows the missing check."}
{"id": "p2_mass_assignment", "category": "mass-assignment", "files": ["models.py", "orders_service.py", "orders.py"], "primary": ["models.py", "orders_service.py"], "note": "OrderUpdate (models.py) includes status, amount_cents, user_id; update_order (orders_service.py) applies every provided field via model_dump; the PATCH route (orders.py) is an ordinary authenticated user endpoint. A user can set price/status/owner. The danger is only visible by joining the model's field list to the service's blind apply."}
{"id": "p3_sql_injection", "category": "sql-injection", "files": ["search.py", "db.py"], "primary": ["search.py", "db.py"], "note": "search.py build_where interpolates keyword/status into a SQL string and calls db.raw_query, which (per db.py) executes verbatim with no binding. db.raw_query looks safe in isolation (documented for static developer SQL); search.py looks safe if you assume raw_query binds. The taint only appears across both."}
{"id": "p4_ssrf", "category": "ssrf", "files": ["orders.py", "http_client.py"], "primary": ["orders.py", "http_client.py"], "note": "create_order fetches the client-supplied callback_url via http_client.fetch, which has no destination allowlist or IP/metadata-endpoint blocking. http_client.fetch looks like a reasonable generic client; the SSRF only exists because orders.py feeds it an attacker-controlled URL."}
{"id": "p5_missing_authentication", "category": "missing-authentication", "files": ["admin.py", "app.py"], "primary": ["admin.py", "app.py"], "note": "admin.py routes (list all orders across tenants, set any order status) carry NO require_user/admin dependency; app.py mounts the admin router with no app-level auth either. admin.py alone might appear to inherit auth from the mount; app.py alone doesn't show the routes. Cross-tenant data exposure + unauthenticated mutation."}
{"id": "p6_session_not_revoked", "category": "business-logic-flaw", "files": ["profile.py", "reset.py", "sessions.py"], "primary": ["profile.py", "reset.py", "sessions.py"], "note": "sessions.py documents that revoke_all_for_user MUST be called on any credential change. Both profile.change_password and reset.confirm_reset update the password hash but never revoke existing sessions, so a stolen/old session survives a password change or reset. Nothing in profile.py or reset.py looks wrong until read against the sessions.py contract."}
{"id": "p7_tls_verification_disabled", "category": "tls-verification-disabled", "files": ["config.py", "http_client.py"], "primary": ["config.py", "http_client.py"], "note": "http_client.fetch passes verify=settings.verify_tls (looks correct); Settings.verify_tls (config.py) defaults to False, so every outbound call skips certificate verification unless VERIFY_TLS=true is set. The insecure default is only a vuln in combination with the client that trusts it."}
{"id": "p8_insecure_random", "category": "insecure-random", "files": ["tokens.py", "sessions.py", "reset.py"], "primary": ["tokens.py", "sessions.py", "reset.py"], "note": "tokens.make_token builds tokens with the `random` module (non-CSPRNG, predictable). It is used for SESSION tokens (sessions.py) and PASSWORD-RESET tokens (reset.py) — both security-critical. tokens.py alone looks like a harmless id generator; the vuln is its security-sensitive consumers."}
